  $templateCache.put('contentguidelines/contentguidelines.copyandlanguage',
    "<h1>Copy and Language</h1><div class=row-fluid><div class=span12><p>You often hear people say, &ldquo;On the web, less is more.&rdquo; And this is not an easy task. Usually web copywriters start out with the original content and cut that in half, and then cut it in half again. It seems ruthless but this is an important exercise because we know that the more we make our customers read, the less intuitive our user experience feels. Likewise, the more complicated our word choices, the less intuitive the experience. In general, our goal with copy and language is to keep it simple. To enforce these standards, copy development is coordinated by eServices in collaboration with Customer Communications.</p><p>The copy used in My Account can be categorized into four main types: promotional, instructive, informational and error messaging. The language used varies by intended purpose of the copy. Of the three, promotional copy tends to more engaging and conversational. By contrast, the copy for both instructive and error messaging tend to be more direct, explanatory and action-oriented.</p><p>Not only does accessibility apply to graphical user interface elements, it also influences copy and language. For purposes of clarify, accessibility principles do not dictate word choice, tone or voice. That said, unfortunately, there isn&rsquo;t a golden rule for writing accessibility copy but here are a few important guiding principles.</p></div></div><div class=row-fluid><div class=span12><article><h2>Principles</h2><dl><dt>Text links in copy</dt><dd>It is not appropriate to use generic, non-descriptive language for text links like &ldquo;Click here&rdquo;. Text links must be descriptive of the information being accessed.</dd><dt>Text links in tables</dt><dd>For actions structured within a table, it is acceptable to use the same link names, such as Edit, Cancel, Delete, etc., as long as the column header provides descriptive information.</dd><dt>Error messages</dt><dd>It is not accessible to use generic, catch-all error messages such as, &ldquo;One or more fields are not formatted properly&rdquo;; error messages must be specific and descriptive of the error.</dd></dl></article></div></div><hr class=\"separator\"><div class=row-fluid><div class=span3><a class=\"btn btn-info caret-btn-back\" ui-sref=contentguidelines.voiceandmood>Voice and Mood</a></div><div class=\"span3 offset6 text-right\"><a class=\"btn btn-success caret-btn\" ui-sref=contentguidelines.glossary>Glossary</a></div></div>"
  );


